</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>There are at least two reasons for the continuous and increasing interest in the Riemann-Hilbert problem, Toeplitz and Wiener-Hopf operators. The first one is that the methods of the Riemann-Hilbert problem represent a universal and a most powerful tool that has been applied to a wide variety of problems in elasticity theory, fluid dynamics, physics, geometry, combinatorics, integrable systems, orthogonal polynomials, random matrices, probability and stochastic processes, information and control theory, and in many other fields. On the other hand, Toeplitz and Wiener-Hopf operators constitute one of the most important classes of non-self-adjoint operators with a very rich spectral theory, which utilizes methods of operator theory, function theory and the theory of Banach algebras.
We intend to achieve a breakthrough in the study of a very wide class of Toeplitz operators. We also intend to make a major contribution to the study of asymptotic behaviour for truncated Wiener-Hopf operators, which is a field attracting a great deal of interest at present.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:potentialImpactText>Long-term impact will be achieved by publication of the research results in leading peer-reviewed international journals. This is, however, a slow process. To shorten the time it takes new research to reach its users, all results will be made available online, e.g., via arXiv. We will also present our research findings in seminar and conference talks.

Given the highly ambitious character of the proposed research, we plan to maintain a high level of direct interaction with the
leading experts in the field throughout the project. We think these interactions will also play an important role in disseminating the project results and will help to maximise their impact.</gtr:potentialImpactText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2015-02-17</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/798CB33D-C79E-4578-83F2-72606407192C"><gtr:id>798CB33D-C79E-4578-83F2-72606407192C</gtr:id><gtr:name>EPSRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2014-08-18</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>32404</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>The project has led to significant progress in the study of asymptotics of eigenvalues and eigenvectors of large Toeplitz matrices. This has opened new avenues of research in a field that is being actively developed by leading mathematicians and theoretical physicists.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>We believe that our findings are likely to influence research in other fields of mathematics including combinatorics, integrable systems, orthogonal polynomials, and in theoretical physics.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>73757221-8D0D-463D-B184-75830EBB0BE5</gtr:id><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Other</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/187BEF0D-532C-4F8C-BEF0-2D5A17FF8446"><gtr:id>187BEF0D-532C-4F8C-BEF0-2D5A17FF8446</gtr:id><gtr:title>Maximum norm versions of the Szego and Avram-Parter theorems for Toeplitz matrices</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTit